title: Box for arduino / ramps on MendelMax

description.text:
A customizable box for my arduino /ramps combination for mounting on the MendelMax. Still experimental (yet to print). Slide the base into the 4 clips, then put it on the MendelMax. Cover it up with M3 on the cover. Update (after observation, printing, more measuring, my MendelMax):
  • Only 2 of the 4 arduino holes fit. If you want a good fit, (re)measure the hole distances. I'm content for now
  • My box needed to be a lot higher than 40mm. I used 65 mm (new2.scad).
  • The box is a little bit too long (about 5mm?) to fit on the lower left back part of my MendelMax. Reducing clip width can solve this problem.
  • I printed the whole in ABS during the night. The upper part warped and there are not so pretty cracks. I think the fan was aimed a bit too low. From now on I print ABS without any fan (it only caused trouble and only has small benefits) . Fortunately ducttape is my friend.
  • I drilled the top holes with a 4mm drill to use it with 4.0x60mm screws. Problably have to drill the base plate with 3mm.
  • Still have to see if the polulu's get hot. I think they'll manage.
  • The clip system work quite good. You can set the clearance.
  • I mounted the base plate on another extrusion. Works good, maybe even a better place than the lower left (cables are more off the ground).

I made this model in Blender. I started with a simple Erlenmeyer flask model, cut it in half, and flattened it substantially. To prepare the logo, I imported a .svg of a black and white version of the design. It took quite a while to clean up and prepare the mesh, as I had to combine many of the components, changing their sizes to ensure that the design would print well. I then used booleans to extrude the logo and keychain hole into the flask mesh. (Word of advice: if the booleans aren't doing what you want them to, double check the normals on each mesh, as they will dictate which direction the extrusion will go.)

Creates a rounded half-sphere with mounting holes
that can be screwed to a board to create a balance board. There were other similar models on Thingiverse when I made this, most notably Ankle Board, but I didn't like having the screw in the top, since this is the primary balance surface. I also wanted to be able to scrunch the rounded shape, since some highly regarded brands count their flatter dome shape as a market advantage, and it supposedly makes a pleasant experience. With this, you can customize all your screw dimensions, the screw count, the total size, and the height of the dome. I recommend planning out your board first, so you can print a dome to fit your needs! Also supports wood screws with tapered heads, and allows them to neatly sit in the mount plate! I've provided 3 different models, both with and without support trees that I generated in MeshMixer. The print times were as follows:
  • 4cm: 40min print time.
  • 8cm: 3hr print time.
  • 15cm: 11hr print time.

• Print the 15cm "with support" model. You do not need to add support to your slicer, the model contains minimal support "trees" that should work fine.
  • (5) Everbilt Flat Head Phillips Wood Screws #8 x 3/4in, as pictured.
  • (1) 1x12" pine board, cut to a shape you enjoy standing on.

I was inspired by this page on Circle Knots, https://www.cs.duke.edu/~edels/Tubes/knots/circ/, and decided that if I flattened the bottoms out I could make them printable and interlocking. The different versions have different sets of parameters that are included as comments in the .scad file. There are two basic symmetries, four-fold and six-fold (controlled by the tiling angle), and you can theoretically use any number of loops that is a multiple of the symmetry. So the four-fold symmetry model could have 4,8,12,16 etc loops. Practically the number of loops is limited by how narrow a cylinder your printer is capable of combined with the size of the link. I'm not sure I can go past 8 without modifying the knot function. magic.scad contains my function for sort of smoothly sweeping a sphere through space, which is used by knot_chain.scad. This should build without needing support, as the maximum overhang is less than 45-degrees even though it looks steeper. The pictured sample was built in PVC on my Solido SD300. comments.text: Printed these and had arc/bowing issue in a "z" axis - chain was now straight when laying on a flat surface. Found simple and very effective solution - put assembled chain on a flat  surface and heat it with a heat gun. Then gently push it in direction where it should be and let it cool. Few long flat wooden bars may help to straighten it (or any object with a flat surface). After heating sides may expand a little bit - I gently pushed then back. Now it works amazingly  well - like these "factory" ones. Took me 2 years to figure it out ;)
